Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in amending the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected an attempt to repeal an article condemning the leader of the opposition, Julia Timoshenko.
The amendment, which would result in the release of the former Prime Minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on the commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years ' imprisonment for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unfavourable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider the appeal of Timoshenko in December.
Timoshenko claims that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal article 365 of the Criminal Procedure Code, according to which the former Prime Minister had been convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes.
