Nutrition of children suffering from obesity: No breakfast and no sausage for dinner
More than one third of children between 9 and 13 years of age weigh more than the norm; while 9 per cent of schoolchildren have an extra weight, 5 per cent suffer from obesity.
According to the latest study, children suffering from obesity usually come from families that lead to unhealthy lifestyles.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and patterns of conduct associated with the human being for his or her healthy development.
For example, the sausage appears on the tables of children suffering from obesity almost twice as often as in families with children with normal weight.
More than 19 per cent of children suffering from obesity had eaten fries for dinner prior to the survey on educational activities called obesity is not an accident.
Moreover, families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports, but this is true for most families of modern schoolchildren - only 15 per cent of children said that their parents find time to engage in sports at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was carried out at the end of last school year and involved nearly 900 primary school pupils throughout Bohemia.
It was not an accident for a second year in a row, with the support of Všeobecná zdravatní pojišăvna and Unilev.
To date, more than 12,000 students from grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Adequate nutrition and sufficient sporting pressures are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either excessive weight or obesity.
"For example, only half of the respondents said that they eat five meals a day, according to the luncheon meal scheme, and this is one of the non-preliminary nutritional conditions" says one of the findings of the study.
No lunch or sausage at night.
Experts warn that even relative details such as the regular time of family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 per cent of school families eat breakfast together.
In most families, everyone eats separate breakfasts.
The worst discovery was that people in every tenth family don't eat breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The study showed that hot food was used more frequently in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children regularly engage in sports, this figure decreases more than twice - to 15 per cent - when it comes to their parents.
Set up your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to develop their own menu based on the products offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children between 12 and 15 years of age are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Their favorite food includes a large number of tormented, meaty and sweet meals.
"The great popularity of sweet cool drinks is a matter of great alarm, " says the final part of the study.
As the main lunch meal, the pasta defeated a bird with a slight overweight.
However, children have shown little interest in beans, fish and vegetable meals.
The desire for a healthy lifestyle
The study also showed that children were willing to change their habits in food provided they were provided with relevant information.
"A large number of participants in the study's review team have shown a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they completed the questionnaire after the completion of the lecture on obesity is not an accident," the outcome of the project is stated.
This was particularly evident, for example, in the case of sweet cool drinks, more children have opted for water.
In addition, children were more likely to see bird and fish as the main meal, limiting the number of sweet meals and bakes.
