Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five public tourism agencies were able to work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was severely restricted, tourism agencies at that time were mostly selling tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crime on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, resulting in significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., Czechoslovakia and Czechoslovakia) had not been allowed to travel individually in socialist countries.
If a Czech citizen wanted to go on his own, for example to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was needed; another individual journey was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but they had to either stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have good friends at the agency.
And that wasn't all.
The currency permit was necessary to travel to the West and was not granted to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit, it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) to travel to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their home leave, resulting in a large number of cottages and summer houses, a habit that continues to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989, the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travels, the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox that we are no longer aware is that, until 1989, we were unable to freely visit Croatia, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need for a visa to neighbouring Western European countries was cancelled, starting with a huge wave of short travel, mainly in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't afford to travel to the West, everyone wanted to go there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in tents in parks, as their revenues at the time lacked a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring food (conserves, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a free convertible Czech crown, and decades later our tourists can finally buy Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income grew, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines, as compared to the past, air flights have now become incredibly cheap owing to the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed world countries except the US, making our travel even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution took place in 2000 and the great demand led to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have transported Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flight from the Czech Republic will be sent in twelve exotic directions.
At present, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another important development of this period, which symbolizes our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the U.S. cancelled the need for a visa for Czech tourists, and our country has thus permanently joined the world ' s most developed countries.
For the first time in history, in 2008 Czechs spent more than half of their leave abroad (50.3 per cent); for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during their leave abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
