In Michoacana, the possibility of counting "votes for voice" is analysed.
According to data transmitted to the PDP, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 of the total number of 6,074 protocols.
The possibility of counting "votes" is real, with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoakana, where according to the Preliminary Electoral Results Programme (EPR), the difference between the first and second seats in the Governorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 of the total number of 6,074 protocols.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Institute of Elections, Michoacana (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Saragosa, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral corps had adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the Electoral Code of the State or the Electoral Law Act, since the State Congress approved reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in the electoral process and Governor Leonel Goda Rangel did not include its publication within the time frame specified in the Act in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, on 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJJJ) decided on a constitutional claim made by the local legislature and called "unful and illegal" the voice of the State representative for constitutional reform, since he was not entitled to "accept or support them."
In an interview on the possibility of a vote, Maria de los Angeles Lianderal argued that, with the adoption of appropriate principles, the General Council of the IMM would be able to present a partial or complete counting of votes by the local electoral authority.
For example, a partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes may be made under conditions that: the results of the protocols do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting of documents in the box or he is not in the Chair ' s possession; or where there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, a general count of votes in all the ballot rooms may occur when there is a indication that the difference between the proposed electoral winner and those who obtained the second ballot is less or equal to one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a petition from the party representative and/or coalition that issued the second candidate.
A general count of votes will also be made if, at the end of the normal count, it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate taking the second place is less or equal to one percentage, provided that there is a petition from the political party whose candidate took the second place, in the event of the exclusion of the ballot boxes that were taken into account in part of the recalculation.
It is worth noting that this situation is characterized by elections in Morelia, where according to the PDP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 per cent, even excluding 129 votes in the total of 923 protocols.
